1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,606
<i>Previously on "Timeless"...</i>

2
00:00:01,631 --> 00:00:02,834
Jake Neville, NSA.

3
00:00:02,869 --> 00:00:04,694
This project's command was taken over

4
00:00:04,719 --> 00:00:06,320
<i>by the National Security Agency.</i>

5
00:00:06,354 --> 00:00:08,757
<i>The agents in control
of Mason Industries...</i>

6
00:00:08,782 --> 00:00:09,850
they're Rittenhouse.

7
00:00:09,875 --> 00:00:11,464
She is there right now.

8
00:00:11,488 --> 00:00:12,889
<i>This is Rittenhouse we're talking about.</i>

9
00:00:12,923 --> 00:00:14,490
- They could kill her.
- Monsieur Charvet?

10
00:00:14,525 --> 00:00:16,893
- <i>Oui.</i>
- I have so many questions.

11
00:00:16,927 --> 00:00:18,728
<i>Scary Rittenhouse dude is your father?</i>

12
00:00:18,762 --> 00:00:21,631
The guy who's been terrorizing
me, that's your dad?

13
00:00:21,665 --> 00:00:23,566
I will never be a part
of this. Do you hear me?

14
00:00:23,600 --> 00:00:25,835
Rittenhouse isn't a
choice. It's your legacy.

15
00:00:25,869 --> 00:00:27,637
I'm just a secretary.

16
00:00:27,671 --> 00:00:29,839
Ah, don't sell yourself short.

17
00:00:29,873 --> 00:00:32,075
I saw that drawing on your
desk. You are very gifted.

18
00:00:32,109 --> 00:00:34,610
I bet one day you'll do some
remarkable things at Lockman.

19
00:00:34,645 --> 00:00:36,913
Maria Thompkins was Flynn's mother.

20
00:00:36,947 --> 00:00:38,314
Hey.

21
00:00:38,349 --> 00:00:39,983
What are we gonna do about Rittenhouse?

22
00:00:40,017 --> 00:00:41,469
We fight.

23
00:00:42,453 --> 00:00:43,953
How?

24
00:00:45,656 --> 00:00:48,624
<i>[melancholy orchestral music]</i>

25
00:00:48,659 --> 00:00:52,464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26
00:00:54,498 --> 00:00:57,862
You've been warming this
bench for the past two hours.

27
00:00:58,302 --> 00:01:01,037
Look. I was about to step out
for my fantasy football draft,

28
00:01:01,071 --> 00:01:04,173
but I can't leave you
here looking like this.

29
00:01:04,208 --> 00:01:06,043
House rules.

30
00:01:06,567 --> 00:01:08,535
So, a penny for your thoughts?

31
00:01:08,560 --> 00:01:11,095
Might make you a millionaire, Father.

32
00:01:11,382 --> 00:01:14,247
The rectory could use an upgrade.

33
00:01:15,753 --> 00:01:17,954
My wife was the practicing Catholic.

34
00:01:17,988 --> 00:01:22,058
She'd drag me to mass once
a month like clockwork.

35
00:01:22,092 --> 00:01:24,293
I never really took it seriously myself.

36
00:01:24,328 --> 00:01:27,096
Neither did I, for the longest time.

37
00:01:28,619 --> 00:01:30,612
I have a job.

38
00:01:31,068 --> 00:01:33,569
In the beginning, I
thought it was important,

39
00:01:33,604 --> 00:01:36,506
that it could help a lot of people,

40
00:01:36,540 --> 00:01:39,008
hopefully even bring my wife back to me.

41
00:01:39,043 --> 00:01:42,645
But not matter what I
do, nothing gets better.

42
00:01:42,679 --> 00:01:45,642
If anything, It only gets worse.

43
00:01:46,083 --> 00:01:48,384
I get it. But when times are tough,

44
00:01:48,419 --> 00:01:50,553
you just got to trust
that God has a plan.

45
00:01:50,587 --> 00:01:52,822
What if you could change that plan?

46
00:01:52,856 --> 00:01:54,876
I don't follow.

47
00:01:55,692 --> 00:01:58,428
What if you could...

48
00:01:58,462 --> 00:02:01,497
make a person go left instead of right,

49
00:02:01,532 --> 00:02:03,166
backward instead of forward?

50
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:07,349
What if you had the power to
change the course of history?

51
00:02:08,772 --> 00:02:10,599
Does that mean...

52
00:02:10,624 --> 00:02:14,013
nothing's meant to be?

53
00:02:14,273 --> 00:02:16,607
Does that mean God's not there?

54
00:02:16,632 --> 00:02:17,965
Would he stop me?

55
00:02:17,990 --> 00:02:19,949
What are you asking?

56
00:02:20,663 --> 00:02:21,963
[sighs]

57
00:02:24,988 --> 00:02:27,590
I'm asking for absolution.

58
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:32,061
<i>[tense music]</i>

59
00:02:32,096 --> 00:02:36,066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

60
00:02:37,101 --> 00:02:39,885
Guess this is what North Korea's like.

61
00:02:45,509 --> 00:02:48,244
Listen. Whatever happens,
just do what they say.

62
00:02:48,278 --> 00:02:50,426
Everything's gonna be fine.

63
00:02:52,769 --> 00:02:54,139
Flynn made another jump?

64
00:02:54,164 --> 00:02:57,386
So glad you could finally
join us, Ms. Preston.

65
00:02:57,421 --> 00:02:58,588
Mr. Carlin.

66
00:02:58,622 --> 00:03:00,995
I, for one, am sick of waiting

67
00:03:01,020 --> 00:03:03,782
for Garcia Flynn to dictate our actions.

68
00:03:03,807 --> 00:03:05,493
No more playing defense.

69
00:03:05,518 --> 00:03:07,063
We're gonna take the son of a bitch out

70
00:03:07,097 --> 00:03:08,097
once and for all.

71
00:03:08,132 --> 00:03:09,605
How?

72
00:03:10,644 --> 00:03:13,130
1962. Houston, Texas.

73
00:03:13,155 --> 00:03:15,671
1962. That's the year
before the JFK assassination.

74
00:03:15,706 --> 00:03:16,755
But why Houston?

75
00:03:16,780 --> 00:03:18,941
Do you remember Maria Thompkins?

76
00:03:18,976 --> 00:03:21,622
Wyatt Logan met her
during your NASA mission.

77
00:03:21,647 --> 00:03:23,579
Yeah. Garcia Flynn's mother. Yes.

78
00:03:23,614 --> 00:03:25,014
But what does she have to do with it?

79
00:03:25,048 --> 00:03:28,084
In 1962, Thompkins was
a 17 - Year - Old junior

80
00:03:28,118 --> 00:03:30,143
at Sam Houston High School.

81
00:03:30,168 --> 00:03:31,821
The mission is to eliminate her.

82
00:03:31,855 --> 00:03:33,356
- Whoa.
- You can't be serious.

83
00:03:33,390 --> 00:03:34,857
No, no, no. There is no
way that we are doing that.

84
00:03:34,892 --> 00:03:36,025
She's... she's innocent.

85
00:03:36,059 --> 00:03:37,827
We don't expect either of you

86
00:03:37,861 --> 00:03:40,029
to pull the trigger.

87
00:03:40,063 --> 00:03:42,258
Meet your new tactical commander,

88
00:03:42,283 --> 00:03:44,300
sergeant Major Caleb Sullivan.

89
00:03:44,334 --> 00:03:46,202
You just lead him to the front door,

90
00:03:46,236 --> 00:03:47,803
and he'll take care of the rest.

91
00:03:47,838 --> 00:03:49,263
- Ma'am.
- Don't "ma'am" me.

92
00:03:49,288 --> 00:03:51,497
Okay, so, you just
want us to play wingman

93
00:03:51,522 --> 00:03:52,942
to the Terminator over there?

94
00:03:52,976 --> 00:03:54,877
And you? You're fine with this?

95
00:03:54,912 --> 00:03:57,113
You're just gonna stand
there and let this happen?

96
00:03:57,147 --> 00:03:58,347
Flynn's mother may be innocent,

97
00:03:58,382 --> 00:04:00,149
but she still raised a monster.

98
00:04:00,184 --> 00:04:01,450
And given your performances,

99
00:04:01,485 --> 00:04:03,239
this may be the only
way to get this done.

100
00:04:03,264 --> 00:04:05,321
Forget it. We refuse.

101
00:04:05,355 --> 00:04:08,090
You cannot make us do
this. This is not right.

102
00:04:08,270 --> 00:04:11,127
Maybe I haven't been clear.

103
00:04:11,161 --> 00:04:15,031
This operation has been
green - Lit at the highest levels.

104
00:04:15,065 --> 00:04:16,285
It's a go.

105
00:04:16,310 --> 00:04:18,343
You refuse, we will charge you

106
00:04:18,378 --> 00:04:21,613
with aiding and abetting
a wanted terrorist.

107
00:04:21,939 --> 00:04:25,875
So, you can either spend the
next few hours working for me,

108
00:04:25,909 --> 00:04:29,704
or the next 10 to 15
years wishing you had.

109
00:04:32,549 --> 00:04:34,591
That clear enough for you?

110
00:04:34,616 --> 00:04:37,952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

111
00:04:41,258 --> 00:04:43,025
[takes deep breath]

112
00:04:47,531 --> 00:04:49,498
I'm sorry. Agent
Neville's bedside manner

113
00:04:49,533 --> 00:04:51,267
leaves something to be desired.

114
00:04:51,301 --> 00:04:53,069
I guess I shouldn't be
surprised that you're here.

115
00:04:53,103 --> 00:04:55,404
You have to understand
Flynn is out of control.

116
00:04:55,439 --> 00:04:57,540
If this one death can save hundreds...

117
00:04:57,574 --> 00:04:59,691
Save Rittenhouse, you mean.

118
00:04:59,716 --> 00:05:01,987
This is the murder of
an innocent girl, period.

119
00:05:02,012 --> 00:05:04,947
He cares nothing about
history or collateral damage.

120
00:05:04,981 --> 00:05:07,191
And what's his mother? What is she?

121
00:05:07,851 --> 00:05:09,385
We need you on this trip.

122
00:05:09,419 --> 00:05:11,487
You're our chosen historian.
You always have been.

123
00:05:11,521 --> 00:05:13,489
- Go to hell.
- Lucy!

124
00:05:13,523 --> 00:05:16,125
I know we're asking the unthinkable.

125
00:05:16,159 --> 00:05:17,493
This isn't who you are.

126
00:05:17,527 --> 00:05:19,828
You have such a good
heart, and I admire that.

127
00:05:19,863 --> 00:05:22,769
I'm... i'm proud of you.

128
00:05:22,794 --> 00:05:26,385
I only ask that you do this one mission.

129
00:05:26,420 --> 00:05:28,635
The next one...

130
00:05:28,660 --> 00:05:31,018
will be saving your sister.

131
00:05:31,208 --> 00:05:32,541
I fully intend to honor the deal

132
00:05:32,576 --> 00:05:33,976
you've made with Agent Christopher,

133
00:05:34,010 --> 00:05:35,477
and I'm in a much better
position to do that

134
00:05:35,512 --> 00:05:37,280
than she could ever be.

135
00:05:38,081 --> 00:05:40,416
That's what you want, Isn't it?

136
00:05:40,450 --> 00:05:42,351
More than anything?

137
00:05:43,420 --> 00:05:46,422
[machinery whirring]

138
00:05:53,063 --> 00:05:55,576
- Hey, could you...
- Hey, what?

139
00:05:56,132 --> 00:05:57,545
Never mind.

140
00:05:58,301 --> 00:06:00,536
Just so you know, you could
get a little queasy on reentry.

141
00:06:00,570 --> 00:06:03,646
Don't worry about me. I'm
not your dance partner.

142
00:06:06,276 --> 00:06:09,278
[rumbling]

143
00:06:18,488 --> 00:06:21,285
[rumbling and whirring]

144
00:06:24,127 --> 00:06:27,296
[groaning]

145
00:06:27,330 --> 00:06:29,297
Are we here?

146
00:06:30,066 --> 00:06:31,967
[breathing heavily]

147
00:06:33,169 --> 00:06:34,436
[dart fires]

148
00:06:37,641 --> 00:06:39,823
I'm sorry. I'm really sorry.

149
00:06:40,580 --> 00:06:42,436
- Ohh.
- Holy sh...

150
00:06:42,479 --> 00:06:43,912
You did it! Okay.

151
00:06:43,947 --> 00:06:45,338
Um...

152
00:06:48,752 --> 00:06:50,386
I just have to reconfigure
the coordinates.

153
00:06:50,420 --> 00:06:52,227
Do you think Mason is
gonna be able to track us?

154
00:06:52,252 --> 00:06:54,323
Not after what I did to his computers.

155
00:06:54,357 --> 00:06:55,924
[rumbling]

156
00:06:55,959 --> 00:06:57,945
[alarm beeping]

157
00:06:57,970 --> 00:06:59,995
Wait a minute. I've lost them.

158
00:07:00,030 --> 00:07:01,313
What do you mean, you've lost them?

159
00:07:01,338 --> 00:07:03,432
They've jumped. They're no longer in...

160
00:07:03,457 --> 00:07:04,878
_

161
00:07:09,082 --> 00:07:10,939
- Nothing's responding.
- Get them up.

162
00:07:10,974 --> 00:07:12,274
Where in the hell are they?

163
00:07:12,309 --> 00:07:14,176
The system's crashing. Damn!

164
00:07:14,210 --> 00:07:16,879
- [chittering]
- _

165
00:07:20,517 --> 00:07:22,017
Rufus.

166
00:07:23,453 --> 00:07:25,990
- I can try to run a diagnostic.
- Step away from the controls, Jiya.

167
00:07:26,015 --> 00:07:27,051
Now!

168
00:07:27,076 --> 00:07:28,824
Did you know he was
going to do this? Did you?

169
00:07:28,858 --> 00:07:30,492
- No! I swear.
- Will somebody tell me

170
00:07:30,527 --> 00:07:31,767
what the hell is going on?

171
00:07:31,792 --> 00:07:33,162
This is Rufus's doing.

172
00:07:33,196 --> 00:07:34,697
It's a computer worm.
We're dead in the water.

173
00:07:34,731 --> 00:07:36,432
We can't track the Lifeboat.

174
00:07:36,466 --> 00:07:38,434
And Jiya's not to be trusted.
She's sleeping with him.

175
00:07:38,468 --> 00:07:40,455
- Mason!
- Rufus thinks he's smarter than me.

176
00:07:40,480 --> 00:07:41,863
All right, well, I'll
handle this myself.

177
00:07:41,888 --> 00:07:43,527
You get the hell out!

178
00:07:43,552 --> 00:07:46,520
<i>♪ ♪</i>

179
00:07:47,245 --> 00:07:49,041
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

180
00:07:49,066 --> 00:07:52,627
Synced and corrected by Aaronnmb
www. Addic7ed. Com

181
00:07:55,629 --> 00:07:57,918
[rumbling and whirring]

182
00:08:01,867 --> 00:08:04,125
It's us! We're okay!

183
00:08:04,937 --> 00:08:06,504
[laughing] We made it!

184
00:08:06,538 --> 00:08:08,789
You did it! You held
the gun like I said, huh?

185
00:08:08,814 --> 00:08:10,007
Yeah, pulled the
trigger between breaths.

186
00:08:10,042 --> 00:08:11,576
Rufus, you're a badass.

187
00:08:11,610 --> 00:08:13,678
If by "badass," you mean
scared out of my mind.

188
00:08:13,712 --> 00:08:16,113
Okay. So, we just stole

189
00:08:16,148 --> 00:08:18,049
a giant piece of top - Secret machinery

190
00:08:18,083 --> 00:08:19,884
and made ourselves fugitives
from the US government.

191
00:08:19,918 --> 00:08:22,253
- All good.
- You did the right thing.

192
00:08:22,278 --> 00:08:23,567
If Rittenhouse is running the shop,

193
00:08:23,601 --> 00:08:24,772
they can't have the time machine.

194
00:08:24,797 --> 00:08:26,428
Your sense of calm is super annoying.

195
00:08:26,453 --> 00:08:29,026
Rufus, they can't track
us? You shut them down?

196
00:08:29,061 --> 00:08:30,571
Yeah, but it's only a matter of hours

197
00:08:30,587 --> 00:08:32,188
before Mason is able
to counteract the worm

198
00:08:32,222 --> 00:08:33,556
and get the network back online.

199
00:08:33,590 --> 00:08:35,224
How much time does that give us?

200
00:08:35,259 --> 00:08:37,326
The Lifeboat's battery is
drained after two jumps.

201
00:08:37,361 --> 00:08:39,529
It'll need four hours to
recharge, If it even can, and...

202
00:08:39,563 --> 00:08:42,698
Okay. Okay. It's all right.

203
00:08:42,733 --> 00:08:44,490
One step at a time.

204
00:08:44,935 --> 00:08:46,459
First step:

205
00:08:47,326 --> 00:08:49,376
let's go get your sister back.

206
00:08:53,377 --> 00:08:54,712
What?

207
00:08:54,845 --> 00:08:56,412
I think that's reckless.

208
00:08:56,446 --> 00:08:57,580
Flynn is still out there...

209
00:08:57,614 --> 00:08:59,148
With all due respect, ma'am,

210
00:08:59,182 --> 00:09:02,326
we don't work for the
government anymore.

211
00:09:03,453 --> 00:09:05,521
I think Lucy deserves a shot.

212
00:09:06,683 --> 00:09:08,552
I'll start the charge.

213
00:09:10,665 --> 00:09:11,892
[laughing, crying]

214
00:09:11,917 --> 00:09:13,290
Thank you.

215
00:09:14,354 --> 00:09:16,088
[grunts] Okay.

216
00:09:16,233 --> 00:09:17,600
Thank you.

217
00:09:17,634 --> 00:09:19,435
[laughs]

218
00:09:19,469 --> 00:09:20,503
So, what's the plan?

219
00:09:20,537 --> 00:09:22,405
Okay, so, um,

220
00:09:22,439 --> 00:09:24,517
we go to 1979, UC Berkeley,

221
00:09:24,542 --> 00:09:27,209
and we make sure that my
mom and Henry Wallace meet.

222
00:09:27,244 --> 00:09:28,315
[laughing]

223
00:09:28,340 --> 00:09:30,046
They always said that it
was love at first sight.

224
00:09:30,080 --> 00:09:32,048
They knew the minute that they
laid their eyes on each other.

225
00:09:32,082 --> 00:09:34,584
Well, let's go play cupid.

226
00:09:34,618 --> 00:09:37,170
- [laughs]
- [alarm sounding]

227
00:09:38,822 --> 00:09:40,271
It's Flynn.

228
00:09:40,824 --> 00:09:42,895
He's jumped.

229
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:44,297
Where?

230
00:09:45,128 --> 00:09:48,097
<i>[dark music]</i>

231
00:09:48,131 --> 00:09:51,137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

232
00:10:03,013 --> 00:10:05,514
[whispering inaudibly]

233
00:10:15,692 --> 00:10:18,594
Frankie says you have something
of vital interest to me.

234
00:10:19,863 --> 00:10:21,831
These tax ledgers were seized

235
00:10:21,865 --> 00:10:23,666
during the raid on one
of your establishments

236
00:10:23,700 --> 00:10:25,258
a few years ago.

237
00:10:25,802 --> 00:10:28,938
Key evidence for the tax evasion case

238
00:10:28,972 --> 00:10:30,881
they're building against you.

239
00:10:40,350 --> 00:10:41,817
Where'd you get these?

240
00:10:41,852 --> 00:10:44,123
Post office, believe it or not.

241
00:10:44,321 --> 00:10:46,286
Treasury Department keeps a...

242
00:10:46,311 --> 00:10:49,850
poorly guarded file
room there, Mr. Capone.

243
00:10:56,386 --> 00:10:58,432
That's your big gift?

244
00:11:00,137 --> 00:11:02,471
As if they're gonna
get me for tax evasion.

245
00:11:02,506 --> 00:11:03,706
Get him out of here.

246
00:11:03,740 --> 00:11:05,474
I also have this letter

247
00:11:05,509 --> 00:11:08,222
from your accountant, Mr. Mattingly.

248
00:11:10,914 --> 00:11:14,550
He makes some fairly
scandalous accusations.

249
00:11:19,322 --> 00:11:21,857
With this evidence, believe me,

250
00:11:21,892 --> 00:11:23,893
you'd be going to prison.

251
00:11:27,097 --> 00:11:29,065
Pay Mr. Mattingly a visit.

252
00:11:29,099 --> 00:11:31,600
Make sure he can't
write any more letters.

253
00:11:35,933 --> 00:11:38,106
I guess I owe you a debt of gratitude.

254
00:11:38,131 --> 00:11:39,746
<i>♪ ♪</i>

255
00:11:39,794 --> 00:11:41,394
<i>What the hell are we supposed to do?</i>

256
00:11:41,429 --> 00:11:43,863
It's one problem at a time.

257
00:11:43,898 --> 00:11:46,933
And right now that is Flynn
taking the Mothership to 1931.

258
00:11:46,968 --> 00:11:49,569
Except now Rittenhouse has
taken over Mason Industries,

259
00:11:49,604 --> 00:11:52,551
and they might be ten
times worse than Flynn.

260
00:11:54,434 --> 00:11:55,809
Maybe we're fighting the wrong battle.

261
00:11:55,843 --> 00:11:57,243
You're the one who
said we can't let Flynn

262
00:11:57,278 --> 00:11:59,379
take a wrecking ball to
everyone and everything.

263
00:11:59,413 --> 00:12:02,557
That was before we stole a
time machine, became fugitives,

264
00:12:02,582 --> 00:12:05,419
and Jiya was forced to work next
to a bunch of homicidal dicks!

265
00:12:05,444 --> 00:12:07,887
Rufus, like it or not,
we're the only ones

266
00:12:07,922 --> 00:12:09,389
who can stop Flynn from hurting people.

267
00:12:09,423 --> 00:12:12,364
And what about my sister, huh?

268
00:12:13,044 --> 00:12:15,228
I mean, this was my last
shot. If we don't do this now,

269
00:12:15,262 --> 00:12:17,130
i may never see my sister again.

270
00:12:17,164 --> 00:12:19,499
They track us down after we get
back from Chicago, It is over.

271
00:12:19,533 --> 00:12:20,900
My sister will be gone forever.

272
00:12:20,935 --> 00:12:22,836
Okay, look, I get it.

273
00:12:22,870 --> 00:12:25,782
None of us should have
to give up our families.

274
00:12:26,941 --> 00:12:28,475
I know. I'm the last person
that should be saying that,

275
00:12:28,509 --> 00:12:30,410
because I'm the selfish
ass that went after my wife,

276
00:12:30,444 --> 00:12:31,829
but still...

277
00:12:32,713 --> 00:12:36,219
letting Flynn murder through time...

278
00:12:36,851 --> 00:12:38,618
that's madness.

279
00:12:38,653 --> 00:12:41,670
And I think somewhere deep
down, we all can admit that.

280
00:12:42,156 --> 00:12:45,887
Rittenhouse or not, Flynn's not
gonna stop until we stop him.

281
00:12:45,912 --> 00:12:48,128
So, why us?

282
00:12:48,162 --> 00:12:49,863
There's nobody else but us.

283
00:12:55,302 --> 00:12:58,304
[phone buzzing]

284
00:13:00,975 --> 00:13:03,638
- Hello? <i>
- Jiya, It's me. Are you okay?</i>

285
00:13:03,663 --> 00:13:05,845
Rufus, what... did you slip me a burner?

286
00:13:05,880 --> 00:13:07,741
Yeah. I got it from watching
"The Wire." Listen...

287
00:13:07,766 --> 00:13:09,716
- Okay, where are you? <i>
- I don't have a lot of time,</i>

288
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:11,998
right now... you are
in a lot of trouble.

289
00:13:12,023 --> 00:13:13,720
Whatever you did shut down the network.

290
00:13:13,745 --> 00:13:15,912
Mason's pissed. He's gonna
get it up and running again,

291
00:13:15,937 --> 00:13:17,157
and then he's going to find you.

292
00:13:17,191 --> 00:13:18,858
That's why I'm going to
need you to run interference.

293
00:13:18,893 --> 00:13:20,560
How the hell am I supposed to do that?

294
00:13:20,594 --> 00:13:22,796
Delay. Distract. Do whatever you can

295
00:13:22,830 --> 00:13:25,842
to keep them off of our
backs as long as you can.

296
00:13:25,867 --> 00:13:27,400
Rufus, these guys are everywhere.

297
00:13:27,435 --> 00:13:31,396
Jiya, we can't let them have
the time machine, all right?

298
00:13:31,421 --> 00:13:34,507
<i>I'm so sorry for
putting you on the spot.</i>

299
00:13:34,532 --> 00:13:36,166
The last thing I ever wanted was

300
00:13:36,210 --> 00:13:38,378
for you to become a
double agent... believe me.

301
00:13:38,412 --> 00:13:39,512
<i>I know how hard it is.</i>

302
00:13:39,547 --> 00:13:40,847
What do you mean?

303
00:13:40,881 --> 00:13:42,482
What the hell are you talking about?

304
00:13:42,516 --> 00:13:44,584
I'll explain everything to you, I swear.

305
00:13:44,618 --> 00:13:47,754
<i>But you have to do this. We need you.</i>

306
00:13:48,264 --> 00:13:49,838
I need you.

307
00:13:51,859 --> 00:13:53,312
Okay.

308
00:13:54,095 --> 00:13:55,895
Okay, just come back to me safe.

309
00:13:56,711 --> 00:13:59,633
<i>- Promise?</i>
- You too.

310
00:14:00,009 --> 00:14:02,562
I wouldn't be able to live with myself.

311
00:14:05,039 --> 00:14:08,007
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

312
00:14:08,042 --> 00:14:11,077
<i>♪ ♪</i>

313
00:14:11,112 --> 00:14:14,047
- Hi. What's up?
- Who were you talking to?

314
00:14:16,217 --> 00:14:17,784
Myself.

315
00:14:17,818 --> 00:14:20,164
I come here to think, clear my mind.

316
00:14:20,242 --> 00:14:22,222
There's a lot going on.

317
00:14:22,256 --> 00:14:24,124
Empty your pockets.

318
00:14:24,158 --> 00:14:25,391
[scoffs]

319
00:14:25,426 --> 00:14:26,526
Okay, a little handsy there.

320
00:14:26,560 --> 00:14:28,648
I don't remember swiping right.

321
00:14:44,779 --> 00:14:47,925
<i>♪ ♪</i>

322
00:14:47,950 --> 00:14:50,300
You think I was born yesterday?

323
00:14:50,816 --> 00:14:52,542
Hey, Singer!

324
00:14:55,550 --> 00:14:58,678
Put her on ice. She
doesn't leave the building.

325
00:15:05,833 --> 00:15:08,835
[whirring]

326
00:15:12,883 --> 00:15:14,717
Be careful.

327
00:15:22,116 --> 00:15:24,250
Oh, my God, you guys, this is terrible.

328
00:15:24,285 --> 00:15:25,752
We stand out like sore thumbs.

329
00:15:25,786 --> 00:15:27,453
Well, there's no time to go shopping.

330
00:15:27,488 --> 00:15:28,688
Flynn's already way ahead of us.

331
00:15:28,722 --> 00:15:29,856
I saw we own it,

332
00:15:29,890 --> 00:15:31,291
embrace our fashion - Forwardness,

333
00:15:31,325 --> 00:15:33,359
stop Flynn, and get
the hell out of here.

334
00:15:33,394 --> 00:15:34,961
What if Flynn has already done

335
00:15:34,995 --> 00:15:36,863
whatever it is he came here to do?

336
00:15:36,897 --> 00:15:39,966
So, March 13, 1931, Chicago.

337
00:15:40,255 --> 00:15:41,334
Where's Flynn headed?

338
00:15:41,368 --> 00:15:43,536
There's only one place I can think of.

339
00:15:43,571 --> 00:15:45,338
What can I say?

340
00:15:45,372 --> 00:15:47,207
The crooked lawyers for the prosecution

341
00:15:47,241 --> 00:15:49,843
somehow lost all the
evidence they had on me.

342
00:15:49,877 --> 00:15:51,211
But you ask me?

343
00:15:51,245 --> 00:15:53,546
They never had it in the first place.

344
00:15:53,787 --> 00:15:57,050
That's Al Capone? He looks so young.

345
00:15:57,084 --> 00:15:59,519
He was only 26 when
he became a crime boss.

346
00:15:59,553 --> 00:16:01,020
And lost them in bank failures.

347
00:16:01,055 --> 00:16:03,781
They should be the ones going on trial.

348
00:16:04,344 --> 00:16:06,159
Is he not afraid to be
out in the open like this?

349
00:16:06,193 --> 00:16:07,493
The people of Chicago loved him.

350
00:16:07,528 --> 00:16:09,562
They would chant his name at Cubs games.

351
00:16:09,597 --> 00:16:10,954
So, It's true, then?

352
00:16:10,979 --> 00:16:13,333
All charges against
you have been dropped?

353
00:16:13,367 --> 00:16:16,302
With no evidence, the
honorable Judge Wilkerson

354
00:16:16,337 --> 00:16:19,086
had no choice but to drop the case.

355
00:16:19,340 --> 00:16:21,074
Justice has been served.

356
00:16:21,108 --> 00:16:22,876
[applause]

357
00:16:24,464 --> 00:16:26,145
Wait, wait, wait. This isn't right.

358
00:16:26,180 --> 00:16:27,847
Guys, look.

359
00:16:27,882 --> 00:16:30,049
<i>♪ ♪</i>

360
00:16:30,084 --> 00:16:31,417
Go, go, go.

361
00:16:31,452 --> 00:16:34,454
[camera flashes firing]

362
00:16:44,028 --> 00:16:47,100
Capone is supposed to be going
to prison for tax evasion today.

363
00:16:47,134 --> 00:16:48,442
Flynn must have gotten him off somehow.

364
00:16:48,467 --> 00:16:50,216
Well, that's not troubling at all.

365
00:16:58,448 --> 00:17:00,113
For some reason, none of them good,

366
00:17:00,147 --> 00:17:01,948
flynn has already wormed
his way in with Capone.

367
00:17:01,982 --> 00:17:03,549
Well, with all that mob muscle,

368
00:17:03,584 --> 00:17:05,418
it's gonna be hard to get
close to Flynn or Capone.

369
00:17:05,452 --> 00:17:07,954
Which makes this a
first - Class, grade - A cluster...

370
00:17:07,988 --> 00:17:10,071
- Maybe he can help.
- Mr. Ness,

371
00:17:10,096 --> 00:17:13,071
it appears if Al Capone
is the Untouchable One.

372
00:17:13,432 --> 00:17:15,032
Got a comment?

373
00:17:17,298 --> 00:17:19,071
Any more questions?

374
00:17:19,800 --> 00:17:21,567
[indistinct chatter]

375
00:17:21,602 --> 00:17:23,321
<i>♪ ♪</i>

376
00:17:23,346 --> 00:17:24,736
Come on.

377
00:17:29,681 --> 00:17:31,290
Mr. Ness?

378
00:17:31,659 --> 00:17:33,179
Mr. Eliot Ness?

379
00:17:33,204 --> 00:17:34,470
I said no comment.

380
00:17:34,495 --> 00:17:36,431
Oh, we're not the press. We're, um...

381
00:17:36,447 --> 00:17:39,024
- We're private investigators.
- Yeah.

382
00:17:39,450 --> 00:17:41,384
Uh, I'm Connery.

383
00:17:41,418 --> 00:17:42,819
This is Costner.

384
00:17:42,853 --> 00:17:46,583
And this here is our
driver, Robert... de Niro.

385
00:17:47,763 --> 00:17:49,726
We're trying to get
information on the tall man

386
00:17:49,760 --> 00:17:50,860
with the dark features with Capone.

387
00:17:50,894 --> 00:17:52,388
Did you... did you see him?

388
00:17:52,413 --> 00:17:54,214
He's not from Chicago. I
haven't seen him before.

389
00:17:54,239 --> 00:17:56,566
No. He's definitely
not from around here.

390
00:17:56,591 --> 00:17:57,900
Neither are we.

391
00:17:57,935 --> 00:18:00,175
I can tell. Are you
wearing a woman's sweater?

392
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:02,105
His name's Garcia Flynn.

393
00:18:02,139 --> 00:18:05,041
And we think he's
teaming up with Al Capone.

394
00:18:05,075 --> 00:18:07,410
He is the most dangerous
gangster in San Francisco.

395
00:18:07,444 --> 00:18:09,545
William Randolph Hearst...
he hired us himself

396
00:18:09,580 --> 00:18:10,921
to dig up some dirt on him

397
00:18:10,946 --> 00:18:12,180
and try and get him off the streets.

398
00:18:12,205 --> 00:18:14,672
Yeah. And whatever he's
up to with Capone...

399
00:18:14,938 --> 00:18:17,286
it's way worse than tax evasion.

400
00:18:17,321 --> 00:18:19,389
You know, I told them... going
after Capone for his taxes

401
00:18:19,423 --> 00:18:20,690
would never work.

402
00:18:20,724 --> 00:18:24,192
Well, It could've worked.

403
00:18:26,902 --> 00:18:29,011
[pounds on door] Hey!

404
00:18:29,036 --> 00:18:31,081
Hey! Bathroom break?

405
00:18:39,977 --> 00:18:43,246
The burner... we couldn't track it.

406
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:45,531
Your boyfriend covered every base.

407
00:18:45,556 --> 00:18:47,457
Where are they, Jiya?

408
00:18:47,618 --> 00:18:50,153
- Where the hell is my machine?
- I don't know.

409
00:18:50,443 --> 00:18:52,388
And you expect us to believe you?

410
00:18:52,423 --> 00:18:53,801
Look, he didn't say. He just...

411
00:18:53,826 --> 00:18:55,291
he just said he was worried about me.

412
00:18:55,325 --> 00:18:57,326
Do you have any idea how
much trouble you're in?

413
00:18:57,361 --> 00:19:00,554
This is the National Security
Agency. Need I remind you?

414
00:19:01,932 --> 00:19:03,484
Be smart.

415
00:19:03,519 --> 00:19:04,777
Play ball.

416
00:19:04,802 --> 00:19:06,242
[scoffs]

417
00:19:06,869 --> 00:19:09,143
Oh, what's so funny?

418
00:19:09,932 --> 00:19:13,509
You know, my first day on
the job, I was so scared,

419
00:19:13,544 --> 00:19:15,081
intimidated.

420
00:19:16,525 --> 00:19:19,487
I... i was in awe of you.

421
00:19:20,050 --> 00:19:22,544
I mean, I was coming to work
for <i>the</i> Connor Mason.

422
00:19:22,569 --> 00:19:24,854
I mean, my... my hero.

423
00:19:24,888 --> 00:19:27,489
All I wanted to do
was to make you proud.

424
00:19:27,514 --> 00:19:29,934
Right now, It's like
that moment where...

425
00:19:29,960 --> 00:19:32,528
where Dorothy pulls back the curtain,

426
00:19:32,563 --> 00:19:35,740
and she sees the Wizard
for who he truly is:

427
00:19:36,265 --> 00:19:37,896
a coward.

428
00:19:47,859 --> 00:19:50,728
Do you really think that this, um,

429
00:19:51,315 --> 00:19:55,651
childish, plucky snark
is going to help you?

430
00:19:56,009 --> 00:19:57,954
This is the real world.

431
00:19:57,988 --> 00:20:01,820
You take your time,
you think, and decide:

432
00:20:02,344 --> 00:20:06,875
help us or be arrested and incarcerated.

433
00:20:18,041 --> 00:20:21,313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

434
00:20:22,996 --> 00:20:24,596
[lock thuds]

435
00:20:30,721 --> 00:20:33,526
Nice place. Very cozy.

436
00:20:33,551 --> 00:20:35,992
It's a rat trap.

437
00:20:36,026 --> 00:20:39,529
Capone was tipped off
as to where I lived,

438
00:20:39,563 --> 00:20:42,865
so started getting death threats,

439
00:20:42,900 --> 00:20:45,535
occasional brick through the window.

440
00:20:45,569 --> 00:20:49,038
Sent my wife to Cincinnati
to stay with her sister,

441
00:20:49,606 --> 00:20:51,507
and I moved in here.

442
00:20:52,209 --> 00:20:53,876
How do you cope with all that?

443
00:20:53,994 --> 00:20:58,049
Loved ones and family
in that much danger...

444
00:20:58,197 --> 00:21:00,072
How do you still go after Capone?

445
00:21:00,097 --> 00:21:02,065
Well, how could I not?

446
00:21:02,090 --> 00:21:05,166
Couldn't look my wife in the eye
and tell her that I'd given up.

447
00:21:05,656 --> 00:21:08,095
Couldn't look myself in the mirror.

448
00:21:08,401 --> 00:21:10,368
Where could we find Capone right now?

449
00:21:10,403 --> 00:21:11,870
We are in a little bit of a time - Crunch.

450
00:21:11,904 --> 00:21:15,206
Garcia Flynn is very dangerous.

451
00:21:15,241 --> 00:21:16,708
And Capone isn't?

452
00:21:16,742 --> 00:21:18,476
Not by comparison.

453
00:21:18,511 --> 00:21:20,412
Capone? The man responsible

454
00:21:20,446 --> 00:21:22,080
for the Saint Valentine's Day Massacre?

455
00:21:22,114 --> 00:21:23,648
I think we can all agree that both men

456
00:21:23,682 --> 00:21:25,393
are incredibly dangerous.

457
00:21:25,418 --> 00:21:27,318
Why don't we just focus on finding them

458
00:21:27,353 --> 00:21:28,953
and stopping them from
doing whatever it is

459
00:21:28,978 --> 00:21:30,348
- They're planning on doing?
- [pounding at door]

460
00:21:30,770 --> 00:21:31,856
[pounding continues]

461
00:21:31,973 --> 00:21:33,792
It's okay. That's Billy.
He's one of my guys.

462
00:21:33,826 --> 00:21:35,281
Come in.

463
00:21:40,453 --> 00:21:43,455
[rapid gunfire]

464
00:22:04,824 --> 00:22:07,826
No. No. No, no, no, no, no.

465
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:12,964
What? No.

466
00:22:12,998 --> 00:22:14,666
Eliot Ness... he can't be dead.

467
00:22:14,700 --> 00:22:16,434
He's not supposed to
die for another 26 years.

468
00:22:16,469 --> 00:22:17,669
How'd they even know he was here?

469
00:22:17,703 --> 00:22:19,437
How do you think? Flynn.

470
00:22:19,472 --> 00:22:21,885
This can't be happening. I mean,
capone is out there on the loose,

471
00:22:21,910 --> 00:22:24,209
and the only guy that
can stop him is gone!

472
00:22:24,743 --> 00:22:26,214
We got to get out of here right now.

473
00:22:26,239 --> 00:22:27,712
We're just supposed to
leave him here like this?

474
00:22:27,746 --> 00:22:29,284
What do you want to
do? Wait for the cops?

475
00:22:29,309 --> 00:22:30,482
We don't have IDs.

476
00:22:30,516 --> 00:22:32,984
I'm wearing button - Fly
jeans from The Gap.

477
00:22:33,018 --> 00:22:34,686
There's nothing we can do.

478
00:22:34,720 --> 00:22:38,324
<i>♪ ♪</i>

479
00:22:39,358 --> 00:22:42,494
[sirens wailing]

480
00:22:47,867 --> 00:22:50,292
- Where are we going?
- To find Capone.

481
00:22:50,317 --> 00:22:53,684
- What about Flynn?
- One problem at a time.

482
00:22:53,839 --> 00:22:56,696
Stop saying that. Why
do you keep saying that?

483
00:22:59,545 --> 00:23:01,479
Do you know what the very
first Delta mission was?

484
00:23:01,514 --> 00:23:03,148
1979, Iran.

485
00:23:03,182 --> 00:23:04,749
That's right.

486
00:23:04,783 --> 00:23:07,229
Go get the hostages out of Tehran.

487
00:23:07,254 --> 00:23:09,899
One of my Delta instructors...
name is Diamond Dave...

488
00:23:09,924 --> 00:23:11,723
he was on that mission.

489
00:23:11,757 --> 00:23:13,525
The plane carrying the operatives

490
00:23:13,559 --> 00:23:15,994
lands in the desert somewhere to refuel.

491
00:23:16,028 --> 00:23:17,228
While it's on the ground,

492
00:23:17,263 --> 00:23:18,787
a Navy helicopter crashes into it

493
00:23:18,812 --> 00:23:20,154
due to the heavy winds.

494
00:23:20,179 --> 00:23:23,031
So, Dave... he wakes up from a nap.

495
00:23:23,056 --> 00:23:24,936
He sees the plane is on fire.

496
00:23:25,326 --> 00:23:27,094
Now, he still thinks
they're 20,000 feet up.

497
00:23:27,119 --> 00:23:29,250
He can't find a parachute,
so he just flings himself

498
00:23:29,275 --> 00:23:31,009
right out the door,
right through the smoke.

499
00:23:31,034 --> 00:23:32,783
Okay, this is all really nice, but
what is the point of this story?

500
00:23:32,808 --> 00:23:34,879
So the guys afterwards asked Dave,

501
00:23:34,904 --> 00:23:36,838
"if you thought we were
20,000 feet in the air,

502
00:23:36,873 --> 00:23:38,640
"why the hell would you
fling yourself out the door

503
00:23:38,675 --> 00:23:39,741
"without a parachute?"

504
00:23:39,776 --> 00:23:41,870
Dave just looks at him and he says,

505
00:23:41,895 --> 00:23:44,146
"all I knew was the plane was on fire,

506
00:23:44,180 --> 00:23:46,309
"and I figured one problem at a time."

507
00:23:47,060 --> 00:23:50,669
[sparks crackle, engine turns over]

508
00:23:53,222 --> 00:23:56,372
First, we stop Capone,

509
00:23:56,559 --> 00:23:58,727
and then we worry about
what Flynn wants with him

510
00:23:58,761 --> 00:24:00,195
and everything else.

511
00:24:00,229 --> 00:24:03,265
So, If Al Capone is
supposed to be behind bars,

512
00:24:03,299 --> 00:24:04,733
how do we put him there?

513
00:24:04,767 --> 00:24:07,996
I don't know. I mean,
without Ness, this is just...

514
00:24:09,372 --> 00:24:10,665
Lucy?

515
00:24:11,035 --> 00:24:12,550
I know who we can ask.

516
00:24:19,749 --> 00:24:22,351
Hello. I'm so sorry
to bother you so late,

517
00:24:22,385 --> 00:24:25,574
but are you by any chance Richard Hart?

518
00:24:25,984 --> 00:24:27,451
What can I do for you?

519
00:24:27,476 --> 00:24:30,746
Well, uh, we need your help.

520
00:24:31,060 --> 00:24:32,712
It's about your brother,

521
00:24:33,896 --> 00:24:35,376
al Capone.

522
00:24:39,458 --> 00:24:41,114
Look. I don't know who
you people think I am.

523
00:24:41,130 --> 00:24:42,430
You're Jimmy Capone,

524
00:24:42,465 --> 00:24:44,332
born James Vincenzo Capone.

525
00:24:44,366 --> 00:24:45,867
My name's Richard Hart.

526
00:24:45,901 --> 00:24:47,146
You left Brooklyn when you were 16

527
00:24:47,171 --> 00:24:49,137
and changed your name for a fresh start,

528
00:24:49,171 --> 00:24:51,206
and wound up becoming
a Prohibition Agent.

529
00:24:51,240 --> 00:24:53,718
And you haven't seen your family
or your brother ever since you left.

530
00:24:53,743 --> 00:24:55,802
But you know what Al's been up to.

531
00:24:55,845 --> 00:24:57,479
You can't read the morning
paper without seeing his name.

532
00:24:57,513 --> 00:24:59,328
Keep it down, will you?

533
00:25:00,249 --> 00:25:03,184
My wife and kids don't
know my real name.

534
00:25:03,219 --> 00:25:04,956
Nobody does.

535
00:25:07,066 --> 00:25:08,556
Did Al send you?

536
00:25:08,591 --> 00:25:11,159
We look like mobsters to you?

537
00:25:11,193 --> 00:25:13,915
You're from the bureau,
then? Is that what this is?

538
00:25:13,940 --> 00:25:15,331
I work hard.

539
00:25:15,356 --> 00:25:16,603
I don't take bribes.

540
00:25:16,628 --> 00:25:17,907
Just because I was born a Capone,

541
00:25:17,932 --> 00:25:19,300
that doesn't mean I act like one.

542
00:25:19,335 --> 00:25:21,002
We know. You're a good
man and an honorable cop,

543
00:25:21,036 --> 00:25:22,440
and that's why we came
to you in the first place.

544
00:25:22,465 --> 00:25:24,654
- We really need your help.
- Who is it, dear?

545
00:25:25,391 --> 00:25:27,326
Honey, It's...

546
00:25:27,351 --> 00:25:29,146
- These people are lost.
- Sorry.

547
00:25:29,171 --> 00:25:32,599
Just gonna give them directions
out of here. Won't be a minute.

548
00:25:38,053 --> 00:25:39,487
Now, listen to me...

549
00:25:39,522 --> 00:25:40,922
Your little brother Al

550
00:25:40,956 --> 00:25:43,464
just sent Eliot Ness to the morgue.

551
00:25:45,167 --> 00:25:47,018
[sighs]

552
00:25:47,917 --> 00:25:50,365
I'm sorry to hear that.

553
00:25:50,399 --> 00:25:52,486
Truly, I am.

554
00:25:53,869 --> 00:25:55,436
But what do you want with me?

555
00:25:55,471 --> 00:25:57,375
We need you to bring
us to see your brother.

556
00:25:57,400 --> 00:25:58,813
- What?
- In person.

557
00:25:58,838 --> 00:25:59,884
You crazy?

558
00:25:59,909 --> 00:26:01,899
And then we need you to arrest him.

559
00:26:01,958 --> 00:26:03,141
[laughs]

560
00:26:04,458 --> 00:26:06,158
You are crazy.

561
00:26:08,426 --> 00:26:09,888
[door opening]

562
00:26:11,756 --> 00:26:13,421
Al!

563
00:26:13,455 --> 00:26:15,223
Where's the fire?

564
00:26:15,257 --> 00:26:18,059
I was having dinner with
Wrigley and some broads

565
00:26:18,093 --> 00:26:22,630
when this Neanderthal drags me
out like I'm some kind of Joe.

566
00:26:25,267 --> 00:26:26,727
Who's this guy?

567
00:26:26,752 --> 00:26:28,479
This is the guy

568
00:26:28,504 --> 00:26:30,605
who touched the Untouchable Eliot Ness.

569
00:26:30,639 --> 00:26:32,401
Garcia Flynn.

570
00:26:32,426 --> 00:26:33,942
Nice to meet you, Mr. Mayor.

571
00:26:33,976 --> 00:26:35,944
How'd you know where Ness was holed up?

572
00:26:35,969 --> 00:26:38,429
- I couldn't even find out.
- Exactly.

573
00:26:38,454 --> 00:26:40,481
He's done more for me in one day

574
00:26:40,516 --> 00:26:43,251
than you've done since I
put your sorry ass in office.

575
00:26:43,277 --> 00:26:45,766
And the only thing he asked in return...

576
00:26:45,799 --> 00:26:47,734
was to talk to you.

577
00:26:47,990 --> 00:26:49,531
Is that so?

578
00:26:49,825 --> 00:26:51,092
What the hell about?

579
00:26:51,126 --> 00:26:52,860
[grunts]

580
00:26:54,875 --> 00:26:56,598
Are you crazy?

581
00:26:56,632 --> 00:26:58,233
I'm the mayor of Chicago.

582
00:26:58,267 --> 00:27:00,421
And also a member of Rittenhouse.

583
00:27:00,446 --> 00:27:02,670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

584
00:27:02,838 --> 00:27:05,813
- Who sent you?
- I sent myself.

585
00:27:06,875 --> 00:27:08,843
I have some questions,

586
00:27:08,877 --> 00:27:11,145
and I need some honest answers.

587
00:27:11,180 --> 00:27:14,282
Mr. Hart, Al should be in prison.

588
00:27:14,316 --> 00:27:16,751
We need you to bring him in
before he kills any more people.

589
00:27:16,785 --> 00:27:19,087
I don't have anything
to do with my brother.

590
00:27:19,121 --> 00:27:21,656
- Leave me out of it.
- You're a federal agent.

591
00:27:21,690 --> 00:27:23,809
I ticket rummies on the street.

592
00:27:23,834 --> 00:27:25,913
I'm no Ness. I'm no Untouchable.

593
00:27:25,938 --> 00:27:28,830
And like you said, I haven't
seen Al in over 20 years.

594
00:27:28,864 --> 00:27:30,632
What makes you think I
could just waltz in there

595
00:27:30,666 --> 00:27:33,207
- And see him now?
- You can try.

596
00:27:33,869 --> 00:27:36,604
What makes you think I'd want to?

597
00:27:36,639 --> 00:27:38,567
He's my little brother.

598
00:27:39,041 --> 00:27:40,675
I love the stupid son of a bitch.

599
00:27:40,709 --> 00:27:44,145
I wiped his damn nose, took
him to buy candy on the corner.

600
00:27:44,179 --> 00:27:45,680
What makes you think
that I want to be the one

601
00:27:45,714 --> 00:27:47,162
- To put him behind bars?
- Mr. Hart...

602
00:27:47,187 --> 00:27:48,802
We're done here.

603
00:27:49,334 --> 00:27:51,486
And if you tell anyone who I am,

604
00:27:51,520 --> 00:27:54,492
you're gonna have more than
one Capone to worry about.

605
00:27:56,892 --> 00:27:59,861
Did you know that he takes
ads out in newspapers,

606
00:28:00,113 --> 00:28:01,546
looking for you?

607
00:28:01,633 --> 00:28:03,868
All over the country, for years.

608
00:28:05,511 --> 00:28:07,316
He misses you.

609
00:28:08,881 --> 00:28:11,749
I understand how hard it
must be for you to face him.

610
00:28:13,208 --> 00:28:14,809
I've had to give up family, too,

611
00:28:14,843 --> 00:28:16,044
and nobody should have to do that,

612
00:28:16,078 --> 00:28:18,377
but maybe he will listen to you.

613
00:28:18,614 --> 00:28:21,330
- Maybe you could save him.
- Al's beyond being saved.

614
00:28:21,355 --> 00:28:23,885
Mr. Hart, out of all the
jobs that you could've chosen,

615
00:28:23,919 --> 00:28:25,386
you pick cop.

616
00:28:25,421 --> 00:28:27,088
I mean, why is that?

617
00:28:27,122 --> 00:28:28,423
I mean, don't you think
it's because you want

618
00:28:28,457 --> 00:28:30,858
to set right what Al has done wrong,

619
00:28:30,893 --> 00:28:33,908
because you know that
somebody has to stop him?

620
00:28:34,863 --> 00:28:37,525
No matter how hard it is to do,

621
00:28:37,869 --> 00:28:39,667
you have to do what's right.

622
00:28:39,702 --> 00:28:41,501
You have to help us.

623
00:28:43,446 --> 00:28:45,456
There's nobody else but you.

624
00:28:51,213 --> 00:28:52,380
Aah!

625
00:28:52,414 --> 00:28:53,681
Hey, watch where you're bleeding.

626
00:28:53,716 --> 00:28:54,849
That's an antique.

627
00:28:54,883 --> 00:28:56,784
Tell me about the meeting.

628
00:28:56,819 --> 00:28:59,620
I don't know what you're
talking about. What meeting?

629
00:28:59,655 --> 00:29:04,132
The one Julian Charvet told me
about in Paris four years ago.

630
00:29:04,687 --> 00:29:07,729
Julian Charvet was killed
in Paris four years ago.

631
00:29:07,763 --> 00:29:09,999
Felt like it was yesterday.

632
00:29:11,934 --> 00:29:14,469
In his last few breaths,

633
00:29:14,503 --> 00:29:16,971
he told me about this
Rittenhouse meeting

634
00:29:17,005 --> 00:29:19,307
where all members get together,

635
00:29:19,341 --> 00:29:21,075
but he didn't have the details,

636
00:29:21,100 --> 00:29:25,131
so here I am, asking you the details.

637
00:29:25,186 --> 00:29:26,796
Try the bat.

638
00:29:26,821 --> 00:29:28,389
Wait. Hold on. Hold on.

639
00:29:28,414 --> 00:29:30,859
The meeting was two years ago, okay?

640
00:29:30,884 --> 00:29:32,819
- Two years ago.
- Where?

641
00:29:33,526 --> 00:29:35,060
D. C.

642
00:29:35,085 --> 00:29:37,325
All the Rittenhouse
big shots get together

643
00:29:37,359 --> 00:29:39,994
to make sure everyone's
on the same page.

644
00:29:40,028 --> 00:29:42,498
But it only happens every 25 years.

645
00:29:42,523 --> 00:29:45,600
- The next summit is not until...
- 1954.

646
00:29:45,625 --> 00:29:47,734
Yeah. 1954. Long time to wait.

647
00:29:47,759 --> 00:29:49,604
Not as long as you'd think.

648
00:29:51,840 --> 00:29:53,441
No, no. Stop. Stop.

649
00:29:53,475 --> 00:29:56,110
- Al, you can't do this!
- I'm not gonna do anything.

650
00:29:56,145 --> 00:29:57,612
He's the one who wants you dead.

651
00:29:57,646 --> 00:29:59,104
But I don't want the mess.

652
00:29:59,129 --> 00:30:01,482
Take him down to the docks.

653
00:30:01,517 --> 00:30:04,152
No! Ugh! [muffled yelling]

654
00:30:04,186 --> 00:30:05,820
Thank you for the introduction.

655
00:30:05,854 --> 00:30:07,551
Hey, thank you.

656
00:30:07,668 --> 00:30:09,824
Between those tax ledgers and Ness,

657
00:30:09,858 --> 00:30:12,840
you killed two very big
headaches for me today.

658
00:30:13,637 --> 00:30:15,783
But the way I see it,

659
00:30:15,808 --> 00:30:17,807
i still owe you one.

660
00:30:17,833 --> 00:30:20,196
And I hate owing favors.

661
00:30:21,048 --> 00:30:23,796
I think I know a way to make it even.

662
00:30:23,821 --> 00:30:26,189
<i>♪ ♪</i>

663
00:30:31,242 --> 00:30:32,281
[elevator dings]

664
00:30:32,306 --> 00:30:34,039
Swanky digs.

665
00:30:34,055 --> 00:30:37,190
Lexington Hotel was the
height of luxury at the time.

666
00:30:37,225 --> 00:30:39,040
At the time of what?

667
00:30:39,548 --> 00:30:41,495
Hey, are you ready for this?

668
00:30:41,529 --> 00:30:43,564
Hell no, I'm not ready.

669
00:30:43,971 --> 00:30:45,772
Leaving home was the
smartest thing I ever done.

670
00:30:45,797 --> 00:30:47,698
This was the dumbest.

671
00:30:53,260 --> 00:30:54,276
[elevator dings]

672
00:30:54,301 --> 00:30:55,744
Hey!

673
00:30:57,145 --> 00:30:58,799
Frank Galluccio.

674
00:31:02,984 --> 00:31:04,838
Looks like you finally hit puberty, huh?

675
00:31:04,863 --> 00:31:06,130
Who the hell are you?

676
00:31:06,155 --> 00:31:07,956
Who the hell am I?

677
00:31:08,354 --> 00:31:11,389
I'm the one that broke
your nose over Shelly Russo.

678
00:31:12,827 --> 00:31:14,428
[grunts]

679
00:31:14,462 --> 00:31:17,202
Jimmy, Is that you?

680
00:31:17,966 --> 00:31:19,897
We figured you were dead.

681
00:31:20,204 --> 00:31:21,554
Not yet.

682
00:31:22,405 --> 00:31:23,641
Who are they?

683
00:31:23,666 --> 00:31:25,282
They're friends of mine.

684
00:31:25,376 --> 00:31:27,744
Al's gonna be over the
moon when he sees you.

685
00:31:27,779 --> 00:31:29,243
Come on.

686
00:31:30,982 --> 00:31:32,984
- You know what I just realized?
- What?

687
00:31:33,009 --> 00:31:35,478
We're totally the
Untouchables right now.

688
00:31:35,503 --> 00:31:36,697
Oh, boy.

689
00:31:36,722 --> 00:31:39,691
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

690
00:31:39,716 --> 00:31:42,755
<i>♪ ♪</i>

691
00:32:09,587 --> 00:32:11,440
Come on...

692
00:32:27,917 --> 00:32:29,975
- We're up.
- That's great.

693
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:31,131
Where are they?

694
00:32:31,876 --> 00:32:33,043
1931.

695
00:32:33,077 --> 00:32:34,945
March the 13th, Chicago, Illinois.

696
00:32:34,979 --> 00:32:36,670
When they jump back,

697
00:32:36,704 --> 00:32:38,394
we can track their general area.

698
00:32:38,419 --> 00:32:40,217
Well, that's a start.

699
00:32:40,251 --> 00:32:42,252
Get teams ready to roll.

700
00:32:42,286 --> 00:32:46,259
<i>♪ ♪</i>

701
00:32:55,208 --> 00:32:57,242
[electricity crackles, winds down]

702
00:32:57,267 --> 00:33:00,002
[alarm sounding]

703
00:33:00,171 --> 00:33:01,938
What the hell happened?

704
00:33:01,963 --> 00:33:03,725
You said you had them.

705
00:33:03,750 --> 00:33:05,993
[all speaking at once]

706
00:33:16,435 --> 00:33:18,234
What did you do?

707
00:33:19,342 --> 00:33:21,176
I still have to pee.

708
00:33:28,067 --> 00:33:30,467
Hey, boss. Sorry to interrupt,

709
00:33:30,501 --> 00:33:32,925
but your brother's here to see you.

710
00:33:32,950 --> 00:33:34,137
I'm busy.

711
00:33:34,172 --> 00:33:36,137
Tell Ralphie to come
back in the morning.

712
00:33:36,162 --> 00:33:37,796
It ain't Ralphie.

713
00:33:37,821 --> 00:33:41,794
<i>♪ ♪</i>

714
00:33:44,982 --> 00:33:46,349
Jimmy?

715
00:33:46,384 --> 00:33:48,096
I was in the neighborhood.

716
00:33:50,988 --> 00:33:54,339
You got a lot of damn nerve showing
up here after all these years.

717
00:33:54,826 --> 00:33:56,126
You gained weight.

718
00:33:56,160 --> 00:33:58,421
Yeah. You got old.

719
00:34:04,735 --> 00:34:07,137
[laughs]

720
00:34:10,575 --> 00:34:12,209
[sighs]

721
00:34:13,211 --> 00:34:14,544
Who are they?

722
00:34:14,579 --> 00:34:16,582
These are my friends.

723
00:34:16,981 --> 00:34:18,879
Even that guy?

724
00:34:19,150 --> 00:34:20,683
I'm likeable.

725
00:34:21,409 --> 00:34:23,502
You people ain't from Chicago.

726
00:34:23,527 --> 00:34:26,022
We're from California, actually.

727
00:34:26,057 --> 00:34:28,859
Ah, land of the fruits and nuts.

728
00:34:29,456 --> 00:34:30,861
That explains it.

729
00:34:31,151 --> 00:34:33,401
Boy, first time I'm seeing

730
00:34:33,426 --> 00:34:35,832
these famous scars on your
face... that's something.

731
00:34:35,867 --> 00:34:38,080
Don't say the nickname they gave me.

732
00:34:38,488 --> 00:34:39,903
I freakin' hate it.

733
00:34:39,937 --> 00:34:43,340
The papers say you got them
in the war, but come on.

734
00:34:43,374 --> 00:34:45,691
What's the real story?

735
00:34:46,377 --> 00:34:47,957
Between us?

736
00:34:48,880 --> 00:34:50,974
When we were teenagers,

737
00:34:51,249 --> 00:34:53,149
i insulted Frank's sister.

738
00:34:53,184 --> 00:34:55,482
This was his way of getting back at me.

739
00:34:55,853 --> 00:34:57,721
Frankie, you did this?

740
00:34:57,755 --> 00:34:59,089
He deserved it.

741
00:34:59,123 --> 00:35:02,392
Bosses had us sit down, make peace.

742
00:35:03,861 --> 00:35:06,347
Frankie's one of my best guys now.

743
00:35:09,066 --> 00:35:11,230
I'm a Prohibition Agent.

744
00:35:12,803 --> 00:35:14,277
Get out of here.

745
00:35:14,568 --> 00:35:16,206
You're a G - Man?

746
00:35:19,206 --> 00:35:20,787
Not a very good one.

747
00:35:20,812 --> 00:35:22,146
[glasses clink]

748
00:35:27,818 --> 00:35:29,452
So, what are you doing here?

749
00:35:29,487 --> 00:35:30,921
You in some kind of
trouble or something?

750
00:35:30,955 --> 00:35:33,967
- Maybe I'm here to see you.
- After all these years?

751
00:35:34,392 --> 00:35:36,893
Come on. Let's not lie
to each other, Jimmy.

752
00:35:36,928 --> 00:35:39,896
Actually, we were the ones
that asked him to come here.

753
00:35:39,931 --> 00:35:41,197
We're looking for someone.

754
00:35:41,232 --> 00:35:44,280
Tall guy. Name is Garcia Flynn.

755
00:35:44,502 --> 00:35:47,771
Yeah. He was here.

756
00:35:47,805 --> 00:35:49,306
Man of his word.

757
00:35:49,340 --> 00:35:51,274
Did a couple favors for me.

758
00:35:51,551 --> 00:35:53,051
I did one for him.

759
00:35:53,180 --> 00:35:55,712
Did he happen to mention Rittenhouse?

760
00:35:55,746 --> 00:35:59,583
Yeah, something about a
summit in D. C. In 1954.

761
00:35:59,617 --> 00:36:02,085
All of them all together,
whatever that means.

762
00:36:02,119 --> 00:36:04,801
Jimmy, tell me you didn't
come here just to ask me

763
00:36:04,826 --> 00:36:06,379
about this guy Flynn.

764
00:36:13,951 --> 00:36:15,952
I'm here to bring you in, Al.

765
00:36:18,603 --> 00:36:21,571
[laughing]

766
00:36:26,844 --> 00:36:28,345
You're serious?

767
00:36:28,379 --> 00:36:30,747
It's one thing raising
hell as kids in Brooklyn,

768
00:36:30,781 --> 00:36:32,515
but you're out of control.

769
00:36:32,550 --> 00:36:34,117
I'm sorry, Al. I love you.

770
00:36:34,151 --> 00:36:36,918
But someone has to stop you
before you hurt more folks.

771
00:36:36,943 --> 00:36:40,357
You got some balls walking in
here out of the blue like this.

772
00:36:40,391 --> 00:36:42,611
Dad died 11 years ago.

773
00:36:42,960 --> 00:36:45,161
Our brother... remember
him? Back in '24.

774
00:36:45,196 --> 00:36:46,253
Did you know that?

775
00:36:46,278 --> 00:36:47,651
- Do you even care?
- Of course I care.

776
00:36:47,676 --> 00:36:49,633
But not enough to come to the funerals.

777
00:36:49,667 --> 00:36:51,601
Ma was heartbroken, you know.

778
00:36:51,636 --> 00:36:53,603
I started wondering if
you were even still alive.

779
00:36:53,638 --> 00:36:57,663
And now you show up here saying
you're some damn federal agent?

780
00:36:57,688 --> 00:37:00,302
And that you and these
clowns are gonna bring me in?

781
00:37:04,157 --> 00:37:07,817
That guy Flynn said these three
might come looking for him.

782
00:37:07,852 --> 00:37:11,290
And when he left, he asked
me to do him one more favor.

783
00:37:11,856 --> 00:37:13,356
And being a man of my word...

784
00:37:13,391 --> 00:37:15,472
- Oh!
- No, no, no. Please!

785
00:37:15,497 --> 00:37:17,227
Please. Please.

786
00:37:17,261 --> 00:37:19,663
I made a deal to take
out the colored fella.

787
00:37:19,697 --> 00:37:21,798
Flynn says they can't
follow him if I do.

788
00:37:21,832 --> 00:37:23,733
- Can't let you do that.
- Jimmy.

789
00:37:23,758 --> 00:37:25,648
You'd pull a gun on me?

790
00:37:25,783 --> 00:37:27,320
Your own brother?

791
00:37:27,879 --> 00:37:29,280
[gun clicks]

792
00:37:32,683 --> 00:37:34,168
Lower your weapon, Al.

793
00:37:34,199 --> 00:37:36,229
What are you gonna do? You
gonna... you gonna shoot me?

794
00:37:36,254 --> 00:37:38,343
- I don't want to.
- But you want to take me to prison,

795
00:37:38,368 --> 00:37:39,368
is that right?

796
00:37:39,393 --> 00:37:41,761
Oh, Dad must be turning over
in his damn grave right now.

797
00:37:41,767 --> 00:37:43,468
Dad wasn't around to
see what you became.

798
00:37:43,493 --> 00:37:45,118
Neither were you!

799
00:37:46,134 --> 00:37:48,397
You want to know why I disappeared?

800
00:37:48,431 --> 00:37:50,065
Because I saw what you were becoming,

801
00:37:50,100 --> 00:37:52,759
and I didn't want to end
up like that, like all this.

802
00:37:52,806 --> 00:37:56,237
I may be a Capone, but you
and I are nothing alike.

803
00:37:57,870 --> 00:38:00,823
You're right. We're not.

804
00:38:01,284 --> 00:38:02,874
But we're family.

805
00:38:02,909 --> 00:38:06,011
And family's more
important than anything,

806
00:38:06,045 --> 00:38:08,402
which is why I know...

807
00:38:08,427 --> 00:38:10,262
you won't shoot.

808
00:38:12,949 --> 00:38:14,792
[shots fire]

809
00:38:15,154 --> 00:38:16,678
Aah!

810
00:38:18,842 --> 00:38:22,661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

811
00:38:23,132 --> 00:38:25,133
Oh, my God. Rufus?

812
00:38:25,186 --> 00:38:27,522
He shot me.

813
00:38:27,900 --> 00:38:29,760
You got to stop the bleeding.

814
00:38:32,205 --> 00:38:35,173
<i>[dark music]</i>

815
00:38:35,208 --> 00:38:38,076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

816
00:38:38,111 --> 00:38:41,079
<i>[melancholy music]</i>

817
00:38:41,114 --> 00:38:44,120
<i>♪ ♪</i>

818
00:38:55,361 --> 00:38:58,363
[alarm sounding]

819
00:39:04,871 --> 00:39:07,072
What's the status on this outage?

820
00:39:07,106 --> 00:39:08,407
Oh, everything's on track.

821
00:39:08,441 --> 00:39:10,008
We'll be up and running in a few hours.

822
00:39:10,043 --> 00:39:12,245
And you'll be able to locate
them when they jump back?

823
00:39:12,270 --> 00:39:14,413
Within a 50 - Square - Mile radius, yes.

824
00:39:14,447 --> 00:39:17,282
All we'll need is time.

825
00:39:18,659 --> 00:39:20,070
Good.

826
00:39:23,823 --> 00:39:28,714
But if you want speedier
results going forward...

827
00:39:30,737 --> 00:39:32,097
Yes?

828
00:39:32,131 --> 00:39:36,988
I assume you know about
the NSA Data Farm in Utah.

829
00:39:37,370 --> 00:39:40,947
I need access to their
12 exabytes of raw data,

830
00:39:40,972 --> 00:39:43,642
which I have a sneaking
suspicion you can provide.

831
00:39:43,676 --> 00:39:45,533
And what will you do with it?

832
00:39:46,145 --> 00:39:50,282
My team has developed
advanced mining software,

833
00:39:50,316 --> 00:39:52,584
more advanced than anything
the NSA will produce

834
00:39:52,618 --> 00:39:55,009
in the next ten years.

835
00:39:55,034 --> 00:39:57,856
It gives us the ability
to tap into cell phones,

836
00:39:57,890 --> 00:39:59,091
email accounts, satellites,

837
00:39:59,125 --> 00:40:00,992
traffic cams, that sort of thing.

838
00:40:01,027 --> 00:40:04,529
Now, not only will we
be able to find Lucy,

839
00:40:04,564 --> 00:40:07,132
rufus, Wyatt Logan,

840
00:40:07,166 --> 00:40:08,500
garcia Flynn,

841
00:40:08,534 --> 00:40:10,258
and the Lifeboat,

842
00:40:10,903 --> 00:40:12,899
but if our test works,

843
00:40:13,490 --> 00:40:16,750
we'll have the capability
to pinpoint anyone,

844
00:40:16,961 --> 00:40:18,524
anywhere,

845
00:40:18,845 --> 00:40:20,846
at any time you want.

846
00:40:24,550 --> 00:40:27,422
Or we could, of course, just
wait and hope for the best.

847
00:40:30,189 --> 00:40:31,366
[panting]

848
00:40:31,391 --> 00:40:33,600
- How bad is it?
- Bullet's still in there.

849
00:40:33,625 --> 00:40:34,960
We got to get him to a hospital.

850
00:40:34,994 --> 00:40:37,329
In the '30s? No way.

851
00:40:37,363 --> 00:40:39,164
They were segregated, and not good.

852
00:40:39,198 --> 00:40:41,633
Yeah, well, we can't exactly
march him into an ER back home.

853
00:40:41,667 --> 00:40:45,007
Our faces are on every single
government watch list out there.

854
00:40:45,203 --> 00:40:47,038
I'm sorry, Rufus. I'm so sorry.

855
00:40:47,073 --> 00:40:49,908
I should've... i
should've reacted faster.

856
00:40:49,942 --> 00:40:51,777
One problem at a time, right?

857
00:40:53,928 --> 00:40:55,180
Yeah.

858
00:40:55,214 --> 00:40:57,334
Get me to the Lifeboat.
I'll take us home.

859
00:40:58,751 --> 00:41:01,990
Police are on the way. Ambulance too.

860
00:41:02,404 --> 00:41:04,222
I don't know if we can wait that long.

861
00:41:04,257 --> 00:41:05,490
He's lost a lot of blood.

862
00:41:05,525 --> 00:41:08,101
- Can you stand?
- Yeah. [grunts]

863
00:41:09,554 --> 00:41:10,765
[groans]

864
00:41:11,623 --> 00:41:13,290
We're just gonna take
him there ourselves.

865
00:41:13,328 --> 00:41:15,734
Thank you for your help. I
know this was hard for you.

866
00:41:15,768 --> 00:41:17,293
I'm sorry.

867
00:41:25,545 --> 00:41:28,807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

868
00:41:28,832 --> 00:41:30,424
- Okay, Wyatt...
- [Rufus wheezing]

869
00:41:31,911 --> 00:41:35,013
Come on, Rufus. Stay with us.

870
00:41:38,308 --> 00:41:39,708
- [wheezing]
- Okay, Rufus.

871
00:41:39,892 --> 00:41:41,560
- Got to buckle him in.
- Rufus, look at me.

872
00:41:41,586 --> 00:41:43,921
You have to get us back,
okay? We don't know how.

873
00:41:43,963 --> 00:41:45,527
Come on, buddy.

874
00:41:45,810 --> 00:41:47,098
- I just...
- Good.

875
00:41:47,123 --> 00:41:48,325
I just...

876
00:41:48,601 --> 00:41:49,957
Come here, buddy.

877
00:41:50,937 --> 00:41:53,405
You want me to push a button? This one?

878
00:41:53,439 --> 00:41:54,966
This one right here?

879
00:41:54,991 --> 00:41:57,076
- In the seat. In the seat.
- Right here. Okay.

880
00:41:57,101 --> 00:41:58,643
You got this, Rufus. Come on.

881
00:41:58,678 --> 00:42:01,888
[whirring]

882
00:42:01,913 --> 00:42:03,701
Stick with us, Rufus!

883
00:42:03,726 --> 00:42:05,006
Tell Jiya...

884
00:42:05,031 --> 00:42:07,263
We're buckled in. Get us out of here.

885
00:42:08,050 --> 00:42:09,828
- What?
- Rufus.

886
00:42:10,226 --> 00:42:11,593
Rufus!

887
00:42:12,008 --> 00:42:13,687
- Rufus!
- Hey!

